{
  "doc_id": "1459",
  "text": "Whether metabolic and mitochondrial defects represent a cause or consequence of AD remains controversial. Numerous groups propose mitochondrial dysfunction initiates AD pathological cascades and therapeutics should target mitochondrial dysfunction [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The cause for mitochondrial dysfunction in AD remains unclear, however. Many theories explaining AD mitochondrial dysfunction exist. Groups viewing mitochondrial dysfunction as a primary event in AD progression point to mtDNA as a potential disease driver [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Groups viewing mitochondrial dysfunction as a disease consequence propose AD pathology, namely amyloid protein and tau tangles, initiates mitochondrial dysfunction [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Still other groups propose defective mitochondrial quality control and oxidative damage contributes to mitochondrial dysfunction [CITATION_10] . Each of these mechanisms may in fact contribute to AD mitochondrial dysfunction and, increasingly, mitochondrial function is viewed favorably as a therapeutic target.",
